pt recv vax 19OCT95 & 4DEC95 pt devel a cough,fever,flu-like illness & a vesicular rash in the rt arm;presented to MD & was dx w/herpes zoster. Follow up information received. Concomitant vaccination included patient's fourth dose of inactivated diptheria-tetanus-pertussis vaccine (ActHIB). There was no other concomitant therapy. On Dec 3, 1995, the patient developed a fever of 39 degrees C (also reported as Dec 4, 1995) and flu-like illness with irritability, followed by cough on Dec 4, 1995, and a red, papulo-vesicular, pruritic rash (15-20 lesions) on the right arm and forearm on Dec 5, 1995. She presented to her physician and was diagnosed with herpes zoster. A specimen from the rash was obtained on Dec 8, 1995. PCR analysis revealed the Oka/Merck varcella virus strain. The patient recovered on Dec 20, 1995. The reporter felt that the herpes zoster was related to therapy with varicella vaccine. No further details were provided.
LAB_DATA: Polymerase Chain, 12/95, Varicella Virus Oka/Merck Strain; body temp 39C

pt recv vax 20APR95 & 28APR95 pt devel a fever of 103;2 days later fever was 105 & stayed;would not walk;lab eval showed a neg monospot test, neg blood cult & urine;also exp inc SGOT, SGPT, LDH & triglycerides;had an off the wall CBC This is in follow-up to report (s) previously submitted on 5/30/1996. A nurse reported that a 1 year old male patient was vaccinated with MMR II vaccine on 20APR95 SC in the deltoid. Concomitant vaccinations that same day included haemophilus b conjugate vaccine IM in the left anterior thigh. On 28APR95 the patient developed a fever of 104 degrees F. Two days later, his fever was 105 degrees F. He was lethargic and "could not walk for five days". Laboratory evaluation showed a negative monospot test, negative blood cultures and urine. He also expereinced increased SGOT, SGPT, LDH and triglycerides. He had an "off the wall" CBC and abnormal blood chemistry. Lipoproteins were "very high". On approximately 01MAY95 he developed a rash that lasted for 13 days. He presented to an emergency room for treatment. Approximately 14 days later, the patient recovered. It was reported that 2 other patients had a similar experience following vaccination with MMR II (WAES 97050595 and 97120033). No further information provided.
